2–Female":"1142–Afdød","about 1170":"omkring 1170","1142":"1142","1140":"1140","1170":"1170","about 1142":"omkring 1142","Edgefield, Norfolk, England":"Edgefield, Norfolk, England","Walcott, Norfolk, England":"Walcott, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Erpingham, Norfolk, England":"Erpingham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1142–":"circa 1142–Overleden","1140–Male":"1140–Overleden","1170–Male":"1170–Overleden","1142–Female":"1142–Overleden","about 1170":"circa 1170","1142":"1142","1140":"1140","1170":"1170","about 1142":"circa 1142","Edgefield, Norfolk, England":"Edgefield, Norfolk, England","Walcott, Norfolk, England":"Walcott, Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Erpingham, Norfolk, England":"Erpingham, Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1142–":"about 1142–Deceased","1140–Male":"1140–Deceased","1170–Male":"1170–Deceased","1142–Female":"1142–Deceased","about 1170":"about 1170","1142":"1142","1140":"1140","1170":"1170","about 1142":"about 1142","Edgefield, Norfolk, England":"Edgefield, Norfolk, England","Walcott, Norfolk, England":"Walcott, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Erpingham, Norfolk, England":"Erpingham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Walcote","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places called Walcott, Walcot, or Walcote, for example in Lincolnshire, Leicestershire, Norfolk, Oxfordshire, and Wiltshire, all named in Old English <i>walh</i> ‘foreigner, Briton, serf’ (genitive plural <i>wala</i>) + <i>cot</i> ‘cottage, hut, shelter’ (plural <i>cotu</i>), i.e. ‘the cottage where the (Welsh-speaking) Britons lived’. This name is also frequent in Barbados and Jamaica, when emancipated slaves adopted it from the name of one or other of the sugar plantations owned there by English families called Walcott.","History: This surname was in MA from an early date. William Walcott emigrated from England to Salem, MA, in 1637; John Wolcott (1632–1690) is recorded in Springfield, MA."],"variants":[{"name":"Walcutt","meanings":["English: variant of   Walcott  ."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Maud Walcote was born about 1142, in Walcott, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 2 sons with Peter Edisfield."},"et":{"about 1142–":"umbes 1142–Surnud","1140–Male":"1140–Surnud","1170–Male":"1170–Surnud","1142–Female":"1142–Surnud","about 1170":"umbes 1170","1142":"1142","1140":"1140","1170":"1170","about 1142":"umbes 1142","Edgefield, Norfolk, England":"Edgefield, Norfolk, England","Walcott, Norfolk, England":"Walcott, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Erpingham, Norfolk, England":"Erpingham, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1142–":"noin 1142–Kuollut","1140–Male":"1140–Kuollut","1170–Male":"1170–Kuollut","1142–Female":"1